Seriously agree with most of what you said- although unsolicited/unwanted touching is unacceptable in my opinion (not just rape). 

However, with the information presented here, what it seems to me is the primary concern for most of these women was their ‘careers’; so they kept silent to preserve that. This happens in many professions, and unfortunately silence is normalized because most people (men and women) fear losing their jobs, reputations, etc; when perhaps they have obligations (such as children) so their belief systems/morality flies out the window when faced with these types of situations. 

With that being said, the sheer nature of the job of acting creates all sorts of illusions and delusions. As with many professions, people enter into it for different reasons... some for a truly artistic experience, some to be wealthy/famous, some because they are following in their family’s footsteps, etc. So other than speculate as to why these women got involved with Franco, I’m just listening, and what I hear is most of them wanted to work with him due to career goals. They seem to each have been capable of saying NO I don’t want to do this or that... I’m not hearing that anyone was held against their will or anything. The story of him pushing a woman down was completely awful, not sure why nothing was done to immediately correct that...? 

So what I’m hearing also comes down to this: Famous man uses his position to see some boobies and uses his ‘art’ as an excuse for bad behavior that wouldn’t be tolerated in other types of professions. What a big story 🙄 

I’m sorry that these women felt objectified and fearful of working with him, and they should absolutely speak out if that’s the truth; but they have every right to say NO and if there’s a lesson to be learned then it should be to make sure your reading comprehension skills are stellar, and you put your demands in the contract so there’s no ambiguity about where you stand, what you’ll accept or not, and what you will or will not do.
